# .boundary-allowlist
#
# Files in this list are exempt from scripts/check-public-boundary.sh.
# Each entry MUST include a one-line comment explaining why the file
# legitimately needs to contain something that matches a denylist pattern.
#
# Format: one path per line, glob patterns allowed.
# Empty lines and lines starting with # are ignored.
#
# See docs/strategy/public-boundary-STRATEGY.md for the rules.

# Documents that explicitly name organizations to *describe the boundary*.
# They reference "Optiscan" and "viloforge.com" only to say which values
# do NOT belong in public artifacts. Removing the references would defeat
# the doc's purpose.
docs/strategy/scope-and-deployment-STRATEGY.md
docs/strategy/public-boundary-STRATEGY.md

# Strategy doc that names Optiscan in a single scope-clarification banner
# ("Optiscan's own deployment is out of scope here"). The naming is
# intentional and clarifies the doc's audience.
docs/strategy/dashboard-backend-STRATEGY.md

# Decisions log records Optiscan-specific decisions explicitly (D1, D2-D4)
# precisely because they are Optiscan-specific. The whole point of these
# entries is to record the boundary between public and private decisions.
docs/strategy/decisions-LOG.md

# The CI script itself contains the denylist regexes, which include the
# patterns we are forbidding elsewhere.
scripts/check-public-boundary.sh

# Design and strategy docs that contain example connection strings with
# placeholder credentials (e.g. "postgres://otel:...@pg-spend"). The "..."
# is a literal placeholder; no real credential is exposed. Reviewer
# verifies during PR review.
docs/design/pi-usage-reporter-DESIGN.md
